                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1025">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.6354/161: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-26T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 26, 1939—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 26—3:13 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2176. Your 1294, October 25, 6 p.m. was most helpful as the Colonial Office’s
                    figures were for departures from the Middle East. Consequently I again strongly
                    pressed the point respecting the experience of our consumers and asked for an
                    explanation. I had previously informally inquired whether the Colonial Office or
                    the Tin Committee had any information about the possible action of vested
                    interests through pools or otherwise to hold up supplies in the hope of an
                    increased maximum price. I again raised this question.</p>
                <p>The Colonial Office assures me that these and other relevant matters will be
                    given every consideration at tomorrow’s meeting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
